      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How to Handle the First Offer in a Brisbane Sale: Accept, Counter, or Hold
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The first credible offer in a campaign often comes from the strongest, most prepared buyer. The seller's instinct to hold out for more frequently leaves money on the table. Here is how to think about it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most consequential decisions in a property campaign happens early: what to do when the first offer arrives. Many sellers assume an early offer is just an opening bid, something to be brushed aside while waiting for the wider market to weigh in. The patterns across hundreds of Brisbane sales tell a different story. The first credible offer is often the strongest offer of the entire campaign, and the seller's instinct to hold out for more frequently leaves money on the table.</p>

      <p>This is not an argument for accepting any offer that arrives. It is an argument for taking first offers seriously, evaluating them on their merits, and resisting the temptation to dismiss them out of habit or hope.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why first offers deserve careful thought</h2>
      <p>The buyer who makes a credible offer in week one of a campaign is rarely a casual browser. They have usually been actively searching for weeks or months, watching for the right property in the right area. When yours appears, they recognise the fit immediately and move quickly because they know that good Brisbane stock does not sit. They have done their inspection, looked at comparable sales, checked their finance position, and reached a number they are willing to commit to. That level of preparation produces stronger offers, not weaker ones.</p>

      <p>Across hundreds of sales in Brisbane's inner east, first offers within the first 14 days of listing tend to settle at or very close to the eventual sale price. First offers in week one are often the strongest of the entire campaign. The pattern repeats often enough that any seller who dismisses an early offer reflexively is taking on real risk.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What makes a first offer good</h2>
      <p>Not every first offer is strong. The features that distinguish a credible offer from a weak one are usually visible if you know what to look for. A good first offer comes from a buyer who has inspected the property, asked detailed questions, and engaged seriously with the agent. They come with evidence of finance pre-approval or, in some cases, a clear cash position. Their offer is at or above the lower end of the comparable sales evidence for your property type and area. And it is paired with reasonable terms: a normal settlement period, a sensible deposit, conditions that are workable rather than convoluted.</p>

      <p>When you see those features stacked together, the buyer is telling you they are ready to transact. That is exactly the position a seller wants the other side to be in.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What makes a first offer suspicious</h2>
      <p>The opposite pattern is also recognisable. A weak first offer often comes from a buyer who has not inspected the property in person, who has engaged minimally with the agent, who is asking for an unusually long settlement, a low deposit, or unusual conditions. Frequently it is paired with a number that is well below comparable evidence and a vague claim that this is a 'best and final' offer. That is a buyer fishing, not a buyer transacting. Their offer is an option, not a commitment, and they will likely walk if pressed for clarity.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The accept decision</h2>
      <p>If the offer is at or above the lower end of the agent's pre-campaign price range, and the buyer is genuinely strong on the criteria above, accepting (or accepting subject to a small adjustment on price or terms) is often the right move. The discipline here is to evaluate the offer against current comparable sales evidence, not against the most optimistic number in your pre-campaign discussions. Pre-campaign price ranges are estimates of the range of outcomes the property might achieve. The first credible offer in the lower half of that range is still inside the range you accepted as realistic when you started.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The counter decision</h2>
      <p>If the offer is below your range but the buyer is genuine, a counter at or near the upper end of the range is often the right response. A counter establishes negotiating posture and signals that you take the buyer seriously enough to engage. It also leaves the buyer room to come back with their best number rather than walking away from a flat refusal. Most negotiated sales in Brisbane move through one or two counter rounds. The first counter is often where the eventual price is set in motion.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The hold decision</h2>
      <p>The hold decision is more delicate. If you are genuinely in week one of a planned four-week campaign, the offer is meaningfully below comparable evidence, and you have strong open home attendance suggesting wider buyer interest, holding to test the wider pool can be justified. But the risk increases with every week. You may lose this buyer, who has options. The longer your property sits, the more it reveals weakness in the eyes of remaining buyers. Holding too long for an extra 5% in expected price often costs more than 5% in the discount you eventually accept.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The worst response: ignoring or stalling</h2>
      <p>Whatever you decide, the worst response is delay. Sellers who take a week to respond to a credible first offer signal weakness, indecision, or a lack of seriousness. The buyer reads this clearly and either withdraws or shifts attention to another property. Respond within 24 to 48 hours, regardless of the decision. A clear 'no, thank you' delivered quickly maintains your standing far better than a 'we are still considering' delivered slowly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do practically</h2>
      <p>The agent presents the offer with their assessment of buyer strength. You compare it to current comparable sales evidence, not pre-campaign optimism. If you are accepting or countering, do so quickly with clear terms. If you are holding, communicate constructively with the buyer to keep them engaged: a respectful 'we are not in a position to accept at that level today, but we appreciate the offer and would welcome further conversation' keeps the door open without committing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The holding cost is real</h2>
      <p>Every additional week on market reduces the active buyer pool. Stale listings lose perceived value, and the longer a property sits, the more buyers ask 'what is wrong with it?' The cost of holding for an additional 5% on price is often larger than 5% by the time the campaign concludes, once you account for the discount on the eventual sale, the additional carrying costs, the agent's diminishing leverage, and the time and stress involved in keeping a property show-ready for an extended period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do</h2>
      <p>Do not refuse to consider any offer below your asking price as a matter of principle. Asking prices are starting points, not minimums. Do not let emotion ('I want $X for this house') override evidence and momentum. Do not assume that holding for 'the right buyer' will produce a higher result; the right buyer for most properties is the strong, prepared buyer who arrives in the first two weeks.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Evaluate every offer on its merits: price, buyer strength, terms, timing in the campaign. Respond promptly with a clear decision. First offers are often the best offers of a campaign. Treat them seriously, not as opening salvos to dismiss out of habit.</p>

